National Council of Negro Women. A powerful and eloquent orator, Dr. Cole demonstrates her commitment to the success of historically Black colleges and universities, her ideas about the central importance of diversity and inclusion in higher education, the impact of growing up in the segregated South on her life and activism, and her belief in public service. Drawing on a range of Black thinkers, writers, and artists as well as biblical scripture and spirituals, her speeches give voice to the most urgent and polarizing issues of our time while inspiring transformational leadership and change. Speechifying also includes interviews with Dr. Cole that highlight her perspective as a Black feminist, her dedication to public speaking and “speechifying” in the tradition of the Black church, and the impact that her leadership and mentorship have had on generations of Black feminist scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American anthropologists. 0aAfrican American college presidents. 0aCollege presidentszUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aRacism in higher educationzUnited States. 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., AmericanxAfrican American authors. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aBetsch Cole, Johnnetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiddings, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorraine Williams, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatkins-Hayes, Celeste, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatkins-Hayes, Celeste, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilliams, Erica Lorraine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete